{{Infobox cricket ground | ground_name = Botanical Gardens Cricket Ground | nickname = | country = England | image = | location = [[Old Trafford (district)|Old Trafford]], [[Stretford]], [[Lancashire]] | establishment = 1848 <small>(first recorded match)</small> | seating_capacity = | end1 = | end2 = | year2 = 1849 & 1851 | club2 = [[Lancashire county cricket teams|Lancashire]] | year1 = 1848, 1852 & 1854 | club1 = [[Manchester Cricket Club]] | date = 5 September | year = 2010 | source = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/616.html Ground profile }}
'''Botanical Gardens Cricket Ground''' was a [[cricket]] ground in [[Old Trafford (district)|Old Trafford]], [[Stretford]], [[Lancashire]]. The ground was located adjacent to [[White City, Greater Manchester|Manchester Botanical Garden]]. The ground was on land owned by [[Humphrey de Trafford|Sir Humphrey de Trafford]], who allowed [[Manchester Cricket Club]] to lease the ground.
The first recorded match that is now considered to have been [[first-class cricket|first-class]] on the ground was in 1848, when Manchester Cricket Club played [[Sheffield Cricket Club]]. The following season [[Lancashire county cricket teams|a Lancashire team]] played [[Yorkshire county cricket teams|a team from Yorkshire]]. In 1851, a Lancashire side played their second and final first-class match at the ground in a repeat of the previous first-class fixture there involving. Manchester Cricket Club played two further first-class matches at the ground in 1852 and then 1854, both coming against Sheffield Cricket Club.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/616_f.html First-Class Matches played on Botanical Gardens Cricket Ground]</ref>
The final recorded match held on the ground came in 1856 when Manchester Cricket Club played rugby.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/616_misc.html Other matches played on Botanical Gardens]</ref> Shortly after the ground was developed for the [[Art Treasures Exhibition, Manchester 1857|1857 Art Treasures Exhibition]]. Later, the location of the ground became a [[motorcycle speedway]] venue before closing in 1982. Today the location of the ground is covered by the White City Retail Centre.
